"{\n  \"text\": \"So I own a fermentation business. Basically, my job is to ferment vegetables and sell them. Here are our large batch fermentations. These are 55 gallon stainless steel drums because you cannot use anything other than stainless steel when fermenting things because it is too reactive. Fermentation is a highly acidic process. So we use 304 stainless steel drums. They cost a fortune, but they work so well. And if you look down here, this is our bubbler. This is where the CO2 that's being produced from the fermentation bubbles through. Now we do large batch fermentations, but we also do a bunch of small batch fermentations. And these are things that we're just working on, or things that we've gotten locally, or just things that we're trying out, you know, that we're going to sell at the farmers markets. And the farmers markets give us a great opportunity to try new stuff, to commute uh react, you know, get with the community, the foodies of the world, because that's where there are. They're at the farmers market. But also to get more fermented foods out there. You know, if you're just dealing with your regular products, you can't experiment, and that's what these are experimentations. But every single day that we come in, we need to burp these because they're producing CO2 as well. So I'm just gonna grab set this down for a second. I'm gonna grab a cucumber just to show you. All these bubbles just running up the side of that. Everything I do creates a ton of CO2 if it's a good ferment. And that's the whole secret is that you want a living active ferment. And what that does is it's going to crisp up the vegetables, it's going to produce a ton of CO2 that you need to burp out every day, and beautiful lactobacillus and wonderful sour flavors. Just to give you an idea here, I'll show you my bacteria ring. This is all of the bacteria. See that white ring? It's all the bacteria that has piled off of the vegetable. Basically, there's so much that's just fallin